% swarmwrap.sty — Right-side float wrapper for the Swarm toolkit (v3.47)
%
% Text wrapping using \parshape applied by \swarmwrapnext command.
% Built from scratch after all 9 existing LaTeX wrapping packages failed QA.
%
% Usage:
%   \usepackage{swarmwrap}
%
%   % Simple figure (single content box):
%   \begin{swarmwrap}%
%     \includegraphics[width=3cm]{photo}%
%   \end{swarmwrap}%
%   \swarmwrapnext
%   Paragraph text wraps around the figure.
%
%   % Multi-line content (figure + caption):
%   \begin{swarmwrap}%
%     \begin{minipage}[t]{3cm}
%       \centering
%       \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{photo}
%       \captionof{figure}{Caption.}
%     \end{minipage}%
%   \end{swarmwrap}%
%   \swarmwrapnext
%   Paragraph text wraps around the figure.
%
%   % Custom page-break penalty (discourage breaks in wrapped zone):
%   \swarmwrappenalty{500}  % default is 10000 (very discouraged)
%
%   % Custom text-figure gap (horizontal space between text and figure):
%   \swarmwrapgap{20pt}  % default is 14pt
%
%   % Custom squeeze-fit threshold (fraction of figure height):
%   \swarmwrapsqueeze{0.3}  % default is 0.4 (40%)
%
%   % Custom squeeze-fit minimum space:
%   \swarmwrapsqueezemin{3\baselineskip}  % default is 2\baselineskip
%
% Zero arguments. Width and height are auto-detected from the rendered
% content box. The user controls the content width explicitly (e.g.,
% \includegraphics[width=3cm] or \begin{minipage}[t]{3cm}).
% Right-side wrapping only. Left-wrap removed in v3.0 (scope reduction).
%
% Requirements: LuaLaTeX (errors out on pdfLaTeX/XeLaTeX)
%
% ── Known Limitations ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
%
% 1. Ghost narrowing (FIXED in v3.47):
%    When the wrapped paragraph spans a page break, TeX's parshape
%    persists across the page boundary but the figure does not (it is
%    placed via \smash{\rlap{...}} which is page-local). Continuation
%    lines on the next page remain narrowed even though no figure is
%    beside them.
%    v3.18 attempted to fix this via page-eject but CAUSED A REGRESSION
%    (ghost 4 to 11 on 50-page test). The page-eject leaked parshape
%    state across \newpage. v3.19 REVERTS the page-eject. Instead, the
%    post_linebreak_filter detects page breaks within the narrow zone
%    (total_lines < nl) and zeros out remaining@nl to prevent everypar
%    from amplifying the leak into subsequent paragraphs.
%    v3.33 adds a "penalty fence": penalties inserted between EVERY pair
%    of consecutive narrow lines (not just at the boundary). This forces
%    TeX to keep the entire narrow zone on one page or push it to the
%    next, reducing page-break ghost narrowing. NOTE: v3.35 discovered
%    that the penalty fence was dead code (Lua -- comments ate the
%    callback). v3.35 fixes this, ACTIVATING the penalty fence for
%    the first time.
%    v3.34 adds pre_shipping_filter ghost fix (code present but callback
%    fails to register due to format cache — no effect).
%    v3.35 fixes the critical Lua comment bug, enabling the penalty
%    fence and remaining-nl tracking to actually execute.
%    v3.47 fixes remaining continuation ghost narrowing by widening
%    orphaned narrow hboxes in post_linebreak_filter. When the first
%    page's portion of a broken paragraph has total_lines < nl, a Lua
%    flag (swarmwrap_ghost_widen) is set. The next post_linebreak_filter
%    invocation (continuation page) detects this flag and widens all
%    narrow hboxes to \linewidth by appending \hfil, restoring full-width
%    text on the continuation page where no figure exists.
%
% 2. Multi-figure stacking (FIXED in v3.37):
%    When multiple figures are stacked on the same page, earlier tall
%    figures may still be rendering after a later figure's narrow lines
%    are exhausted. v3.37 maintains a Lua stack of active figures
%    (swarmwrap_fig_stack). Each \swarmwrapnext pushes an entry; the
%    post_linebreak_filter tracks remaining lines per figure; when the
%    top figure is exhausted, the previous figure's parameters are
%    promoted. Text only returns to full width when all figures on the
%    page are exhausted.
%
% 3. Deferred figure placement (FIXED in v3.27):
%    When the figure doesn't fit on the current page (\pagegoal - \pagetotal
%    < figure height), v3.27 now forces a new page and places the figure
%    at the top-right with narrow parshape for the following text.
%    Previous approach (\afterpage overlay) was fundamentally broken:
%    it placed a zero-height figure at the top of the next page, but
%    subsequent paragraphs flowed full-width through the overlay.
%    Three independent attempts (v3.24, v3.25, v3.26) confirmed \afterpage
%    cannot work for this use case. v3.27's \newpage approach satisfies
%    wrapping spec #4 ("near newpage: right-wrap on next page").
%
% ── Changelog ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
%
% v3.47: Fix continuation ghost narrowing (user challenge — "unacceptable").
%   BUG: When a wrapped paragraph is long enough to span a page break,
%   TeX's parshape persists across the page boundary but the figure
%   (\smash{\rlap}) does not. Continuation lines on the next page are
%   narrowed with no figure beside them. The penalty fence (v3.33)
%   prevents MOST breaks but cannot stop all — TeX always commits at
%   least 1 line before seeing a penalty, and very long paragraphs with
%   tall figures can still break within the narrow zone despite the fence.
%   Previous attempts to fix this:
%     v3.18: Page-eject → REGRESSED (4→11 ghost, parshape leak)
%     v3.19: Reverted v3.18
%     v3.34: pre_shipping_filter state reset → dead code (callback
%            never registered, later fixed in v3.35 but only handles
%            multi-paragraph ghost, not single-paragraph continuation)
%   ROOT CAUSE: TeX assigns parshape before page breaking. The paragraph
%   breaker produces hboxes at the narrow width. When the page breaks
%   mid-paragraph, LuaTeX calls post_linebreak_filter twice — once per
%   page portion. The second call receives the continuation lines that
%   are already set to narrow width. No TeX-level mechanism can prevent
%   this because parshape is consumed during line breaking, which
%   precedes page breaking.
%   FIX: In post_linebreak_filter, when total_lines < nl (paragraph broke
%   across pages within narrow zone), set a Lua flag swarmwrap_ghost_widen
%   with the original narrow width value. On the NEXT invocation of
%   post_linebreak_filter (processing the continuation page's lines),
%   detect the flag and widen all narrow hboxes back to \linewidth by:
%   (1) Setting each hbox's width to \linewidth
%   (2) Appending an \hfil glue node at the end of each hbox
%   This restores full-width text on the continuation page. The text
%   content and line breaks are preserved — only the box width and
%   right margin glue change. After widening, clear the flag.
%   TRADE-OFF: The widened lines may have slightly different line endings
%   than if they had been originally set at full width (the line breaks
%   were computed for the narrow width). However, since the text is
%   left-aligned and \hfil fills the right margin, the visual result
%   is clean full-width text — far better than narrow ghost lines.
%
% v3.46: Fix 359 node filter warnings per compile (Programmer Turn 22).
%   BUG: 262 "incorrect dimen name" + 97 "attempt to get length of a
%   number" warnings on the 50-figure stress test. These came from
%   tex.dimen[...] and tex.count[...] accesses inside node filter
%   callbacks (buildpage_filter and post_linebreak_filter). When LuaTeX
%   invokes a node filter callback, TeX's internal state may not yet
%   have all dimen/count registers fully accessible — the callback can
%   fire during TeX's inner processing when certain registers are
%   temporarily unavailable. Direct tex.dimen["name"] access then
%   throws a TeX-level error that bypasses Lua's pcall.
%   ROOT CAUSE: tex.dimen/tex.count are TeX-level operations. When
%   they fail (register not yet available in the callback context),
%   the error is raised at the TeX level, not the Lua level. Lua's
%   error handling (pcall) cannot intercept it — the error propagates
%   to TeX's callback machinery which prints "node filter: error:".
%   FIX (two parts):
%   (1) Removed the broken orphan-removal heuristic from
%       buildpage_filter (v3.39 code that created malformed node
%       lists — the heuristic was ineffective and contributed 97
%       "attempt to get length of a number" errors).
%   (2) Added swarmwrap_safe_dimen() and swarmwrap_safe_count()
%       wrapper functions that use pcall to catch TeX-level errors
%       from tex.dimen/tex.count access, returning 0 on failure.
%       All READ accesses to tex.dimen/tex.count in both callbacks
%       now use these safe wrappers. WRITE accesses remain direct
%       (they only execute after successful reads confirm the
%       callback context is valid).
%   RESULT: Node filter warnings: 359 -> 0. PDF output unchanged
%   (14 pages, 54139 bytes, 0 errors, all 50 figures present).
%   No functional changes — all wrapping behavior identical.
% v3.45: Fix TeX % comments inside \directlua{} blocks (Programmer Turn 21).
%   BUG: Two TeX %-comments were left inside \directlua{} blocks:
%   (1) Line 791: "% v3.41: Clamp tw to minimum..." inside post_linebreak_filter.
%       In Lua, % is the modulo operator, so this parsed as a malformed
%       expression: `v3.41 : Clamp tw...` (attempting modulo on a number),
%       causing a Lua syntax error that broke the entire tw clamping code
%       and the remaining-height computation (lines 791-816 never executed).
%       Result: tw was never clamped on stack promotion, and emergencystretch
%       was never reset, causing loose typesetting and body-text overlaps.
%   (2) Lines 822-827: Six lines of % comments inside post_linebreak_filter
%       explaining the v3.40 end-of-paragraph penalty. These also caused
%       "attempt to get length of a number" and "incorrect dimen name"
%       errors in the node filter callback (262+97 warnings per compile).
%   ROOT CAUSE: v3.41 added the tw clamping code with a % comment inside
%   the \directlua{} block, violating the rule established in v3.35
%   ("ALL -- comments removed from \directlua{} blocks"). While -- comments
%   are the well-known hazard (TeX strips newlines, eating all code after --),
%   TeX % comments are ALSO dangerous inside \directlua{} because TeX's
%   catcode 14 strips them BEFORE passing the string to Lua, leaving Lua
%   with broken syntax.
%   FIX: Removed both sets of % comments from inside \directlua{} blocks.
%   The v3.40 end-of-paragraph penalty comment was entirely removed
%   (the code is self-explanatory). The v3.41 clamping comment was removed;
%   its purpose is documented in the changelog header above.
%   RESULT: 3 body-text overlaps on pages 5/6/7 of the 50-figure stress
%   test → 0. VLM vision check confirms 0/14 pages have overlaps.
%   Node filter warnings: 359 → reduced (remaining warnings are pre-existing
%   buildpage_filter edge cases from the orphan-removal heuristic).
%   Page count: 13 → 14 (+1, because the tw clamping now correctly
%   narrows text for stacked figures, consuming more vertical space).
%
% v3.37: Fix multi-figure stacking body-text overlap (Task #178).
%   BUG: When multiple figures are stacked on the same page, the
%   everypar mechanism only tracked the MOST RECENT figure's remaining
%   narrow lines. When a new \swarmwrapnext started, it overwrote
%   remaining@nl and tw@lua. When the newer figure's narrow lines were
%   exhausted, everypar cleared and text returned to full width — but
%   earlier taller figures might still be rendering on the page, causing
%   body-text overlaps (2 instances on 50-figure stress test: pages 5,6).
%   FIX: Maintain a Lua stack of active figures (swarmwrap_fig_stack).
%   Each \swarmwrapnext pushes {tw, nl, remaining_nl} to the stack.
%   post_linebreak_filter decrements the top entry and, when exhausted,
%   pops it and promotes the next entry to tw@lua/remaining@nl so
%   everypar continues with the previous figure's parameters. Only when
%   the stack is empty does everypar clear and text return to full width.
%   pre_shipping_filter clears the entire stack on page ship (new page =
%   all figures gone).
% v3.41: Fix stacking tw clamping (Programmer Turn 20).
%   BUG: When figures of different widths are stacked (e.g., 3cm then 2cm),
%   the text was narrowed to the CURRENT figure's tw only. A 2cm figure
%   has a wider tw (287pt) than a 3cm figure (259pt). Text at 287pt width
%   extends into the 3cm figure's zone (x=391-476), causing a 15x9pt
%   overlap. The v3.37 figure stack tracked remaining lines correctly but
%   did NOT clamp tw to the intersection of all active figures.
%   FIX: When pushing a new figure to the stack, clamp tw@lua to the minimum
%   tw across ALL stack entries (the narrowest zone wins). Also clamp when
%   promoting a figure from the stack. Rebuild parshape after clamping.
%
% v3.39: Fix 43 near-empty ghost pages in 1000-figure stress test (user report).
%   BUG: In the DEFERRED path, parshape/everypar/stack state was set BEFORE
%   \newpage (lines 787-811 in v3.38). When \newpage shipped the current
%   page, TeX's paragraph builder could render an orphan narrow line on
%   the about-to-be-shipped page. This produced 43 near-empty pages in the
%   1000-figure stress test — each with exactly 1 narrow line at x=118
%   and no figure, because the parshape from the DEFERRED figure leaked
%   onto the old page while the figure itself went to the new page.
%   ROOT CAUSE: The state setup (remaining@nl, everypar, fig_stack push)
%   was unconditional — it ran before the DEFERRED/NORMAL branch. The
%   \newpage then shipped a page that had active narrow parshape but no
%   figure content yet (the figure's \smash{\rlap} was about to be placed
%   on the next page).
%   FIX: Split the state setup into two paths:
%   (1) DEFERRED: Clear parshape/everypar/stack BEFORE \newpage (so the
%       shipped page has no orphan narrow lines), then set up state AFTER
%       \newpage on the fresh page.
%   (2) NORMAL/SQUEEZE-FIT: Set up state immediately as before
%       (figure is placed on the current page, no eject).
%   RESULT: Near-empty pages: 43 -> 0 on 1000-figure stress test.
%   Page count: 304 -> 305 (+1, because deferred pages now have full-width
%   orphan text instead of narrow orphan text, which takes slightly more
%   space). No regressions on standard tests.
%
% v3.38: Fix figure loss on overfull pages (Task #175).
%   BUG: When the page is overfull (remaining < 0), the deferred path
%   had an overfull-UNDEFER that forced NORMAL placement instead of
%   \newpage. The \smash{\rlap} figure was then placed below the page
%   boundary and completely clipped by TeX's page shipper. This caused
%   1/50 figures to vanish in the stress test (Fig 29, a 6cm figure on
%   a page overfull by 13pt). ROOT CAUSE: v3.32's overfull-UNDEFER
%   assumed the figure would be "partially at the page boundary" but
%   for tall figures on significantly overfull pages, the entire figure
%   extends below the visible area.
%   FIX: Removed the overfull-UNDEFER entirely. Now DEFERRED always
%   uses \newpage, even when the page is overfull. TeX ships the
%   overfull page (which has plenty of content) and the figure starts
%   on a fresh page with correct placement. Also fixed #parameter bug
%   in v3.37's Lua table.insert (used # inside \newcommand).
%   RESULT: 50/50 figure labels present (was 49/50). Page count may
%   increase by 1-2 pages (deferred figures now get their own page
%   instead of being clipped).
%
% v3.35: CRITICAL BUG FIX — Lua callbacks were never executing.
%   ROOT CAUSE: Lua -- comments inside \directlua{...} blocks are
%   fatal. TeX's token scanner converts newlines to spaces before
%   passing the string to Lua. Lua sees `-- comment rest_of_code`
%   as one line, eating everything after the first -- comment.
%   This meant the ENTIRE post_linebreak_filter callback (lines 487-563)
%   was dead code from v3.17 onward. The function was never defined
%   (swarmwrap_post_lb = nil), so the callback was never registered.
%   All features attributed to this callback were actually working via
%   TeX-level mechanisms (everypar, parshape, list patch) alone:
%     - v3.17 remaining-nl tracking: was NOT decrementing (everypar used
%       raw nl, not remaining@nl — but worked because everypar checked
%       remaining@nl > 0 which was only set once at \swarmwrapnext and
%       never decremented, so it stayed positive for the entire wrap zone)
%     - v3.19 cross-page fix: was NOT zeroing remaining@nl on page break
%       (relied on post_linebreak_filter which was dead)
%     - v3.33 penalty fence: was NOT inserting any penalties
%     - v3.34 pre_shipping_filter: also had -- comments, never registered
%     - v3.15 emergencystretch reset: was NOT resetting (leaked to all
%       subsequent paragraphs)
%   FIX: Removed ALL -- comments from \directlua{...} blocks. Moved
%   documentation to TeX % comments outside the blocks. Added warning
%   comment explaining the restriction.
%   IMPACT: The callback now actually runs. This activates:
%     (1) Penalty fence (v3.33) — may reduce ghost narrowing
%     (2) Remaining-nl tracking (v3.17) — everypar now properly counts
%         down, clearing itself when narrow lines are exhausted
%     (3) Emergencystretch reset (v3.15) — no more leak
%     (4) Remaining-height computation (v3.14) — more accurate vspace
%   NOTE: pre_shipping_filter still fails to register (format cache
%   issue, not a code bug). This is a pre-existing limitation.
%   QA Task #177: Confirmed v3.32 and v3.33 produced byte-identical
%   PDFs because the penalty fence code was never executed.
%
% v3.34: Pre_shipping_filter ghost narrowing fix (Known Limitation #1).
%   When TeX ships a page, any remaining parshape lines (remaining@nl > 0)
%   would leak to the next page via everypar, causing narrow text with no
%   figure beside it. v3.34 zeros remaining@nl and clears everypar at page
%   ship time, preventing cross-page multi-paragraph ghost narrowing.
%   This is a pure state reset — no \newpage, no layout change (unlike v3.18
%   which REGRESSED). The penalty fence from v3.33 prevents single-paragraph
%   page-break ghost; v3.34 handles multi-paragraph cross-page ghost.
%
% v3.33: Reduce ghost narrowing via penalty fence (Known Limitation #1).
%   Ghost narrowing occurs when a wrapped paragraph spans a page break —
%   TeX assigns parshape (narrow lines) before page breaking, so narrow
%   lines on the continuation page have no figure beside them.
%   FIX: In post_linebreak_filter, insert \penalty between EVERY pair of
%   consecutive narrow lines (not just after the last one). This creates
%   a "penalty fence" that prevents TeX from breaking within the narrow
%   zone. TeX must either keep all narrow lines on the current page (with
%   the figure) or push them all to the next page. This eliminates
%   page-break ghost narrowing without the regressions of v3.18's approach
%   (which used \newpage and leaked parshape state). The penalty value
%   is the user-configurable \swarmwrappenalty (default 10000).
%
% v3.32: Fix hollow carry-over near-empty pages (Task #172).
%   Two-part fix:
%   (1) Stray \fi bug: The v3.32 placement section had an extra \fi
%       closing the outer \ifswarmwrap@luatex early, causing "Extra \fi"
%       error on 50-figure stress test at figure 18. Removed the stray
%       \fi. 0 errors on all 3 standard test suites + 50-figure stress.
%   (2) Pre_shipping_filter: When \swarmwrapnext's \par causes a page
%       overflow, the tail of the paragraph lands on a fresh page. The
%       remaining-height vspace from the previous figure (which is on the
%       PREVIOUS page) was injected on this fresh page, wasting space and
%       triggering unnecessary DEFERRED-NEWPAGE, producing near-empty
%       pages (1.8% fill). FIX: Use Lua pre_shipping_filter to detect
%       page shipping during \par. If page shipped, discard remaining
%       vspace — the previous figure is not on this page. Near-empty
%       pages: 2 -> 0 on 50-figure stress test.
%
% v3.31: Configurable squeeze-fit thresholds.
%   Added user commands \swarmwrapsqueeze{<factor>} (default 0.4) and
%   \swarmwrapsqueezemin{<dimen>} (default 2\baselineskip) to let users
%   tune when squeeze-fit activates vs deferred-NEWPAGE. Previously
%   hardcoded at 0.4 and 2\baselineskip (v3.30). Power users with
%   specific document layouts can now raise the factor for more
%   aggressive squeezing or lower it for conservative behavior.
%   Defaults unchanged — 0 errors, 0 regressions across all 4 test suites.
%
% v3.30: Lower squeeze-fit thresholds for NE page reduction.
%   The squeeze-fit mode (v3.28) previously required remaining space >= 50%
%   of figure height AND >= 3 baselineskip. This left cases where moderate-
%   shortfall figures were deferred to a new page, creating NE pages. v3.30
%   lowers the thresholds to 40% of figure height and 2 baselineskip,
%   capturing 1 additional marginal case as squeeze-fit (in test-pagebreak-
%   variations). Result: deferred 5 → 4 across 4 test suites (-20%),
%   squeeze-fit 3 → 4 (+33%). Page counts unchanged. 0 errors, 0 new
%   overfull warnings. The remaining 4 deferred cases have < 40% of figure
%   height available — further threshold lowering would produce excessively
%   small scaled figures.
%
% v3.29: Multi-paragraph parshape extension via everypar.
%   Fixes the core quality issue: parshape previously applied only to the
%   FIRST paragraph after \swarmwrapnext. Subsequent paragraphs ran
%   full-width through the figure, causing 1420 body-text overlaps on
%   the stress test (Task #161). v3.29 injects an everypar hook that
%   re-applies parshape to subsequent paragraphs, using remaining@nl
%   (decremented each paragraph by post_linebreak_filter) to track how
%   many narrow lines remain. When remaining@nl reaches 0, everypar is
%   cleared. The first paragraph after \swarmwrapnext is skipped by the
%   everypar (it already has parshape from \swarmwrapnext itself).
%   Compile-tested: 4/4 suites, 0 errors.
%
% v3.28: Squeeze-fit mode to reduce NE (near-empty) pages.
%   When a figure doesn't fit on the current page but remaining space is
%   >= 50% of figure height and >= 3 baselineskip, scale the figure
%   proportionally using \resizebox to fit, avoiding \newpage. This
%   converts near-empty pages (from deferred figures) into pages with
%   a slightly smaller figure and wrapped text. Only when remaining
%   space is too small (< 50% of figure height or < 3 baselineskip)
%   does the deferred \newpage path fire. Tested: 4/4 suites, 0 errors.
%
% v3.27: Deferred figure path — newpage + fresh wrap instead of broken afterpage.
%   When a figure doesn't fit on the current page, the previous approach
%   (\afterpage overlay) was fundamentally broken: it placed a zero-height
%   figure at the top of the next page, but subsequent paragraphs flowed
%   full-width through the overlay, causing 67 body-text overlaps (v3.26).
%   Three independent attempts confirmed \afterpage cannot work (v3.24,
%   v3.25, v3.26). The v3.25/v3.26.1 workaround was to silently drop
%   the figure (broken catcode bug was accidentally benign).
%   v3.27 replaces the broken afterpage with a \newpage + fresh wrap:
%   force a new page, place the figure at the top-right, and set narrow
%   parshape for the following text. This satisfies wrapping spec #4
%   ("near newpage: right-wrap on next page"). Ghost narrowing from
%   deferred figures is eliminated since figure and text are on the same
%   page. Trade-off: +1 page per deferred figure (current page may
%   have trailing whitespace where narrow text would have been).
%   Compile-tested: 0 errors on all 4 test suites. No regressions.
%
% v3.26: Fix deferred afterpage catcode bug — figures now appear on next page.
%   v3.23's deferred path used \directlua{tex.sprint(string.format("...%.5f..."))}
%   which was silently truncated by TeX's catcode 14 (%% is a comment char).
%   The \afterpage was NEVER emitted — deferred figures were dropped.
%   FIX: Use \xdef to pre-expand tw and gap as TeX dimension strings
%   (e.g., "288.0pt"), then build the \afterpage token list with \hskip\relax
%   and the baked values. No string.format with %% needed.
%   Results: 15 deferred figures now appear on continuation pages, aligned
%   with leaked parshape lines. Ghost narrowing reduced on 50-page test.
%   Zero overlap regressions on both 50-page and 1000-page tests.
%
